  <h2 class="prepend-1 span-23">Game Engine</h2>
  <div class="span-10 append-1 prepend-1">
      <p>
        The game was built using Processing, an open source langauage for developing animations, images, and interactions.
        Since the game is in 2D, the game objects are all sprites. The animation for each sprite is done by quickly switching
        through different images. Depending on the importance of the sprite, the animation may have 6 separate images up to 24 separate images.
        The animation class was a custom built class allowing animations to pause on specified frames, how fast frames should switch, and switching
        between different sets of images. Michael Davis, the artist drew over 600 images for this 3 minute game.  
      </p>
      <p>
        The game has a number of special effects which include custom physics and particle emitters created by Paul Grenning and Mike Salata.
        The physics engine is threaded off from the main
        game loop and is capable of being split into numerous threads if there are to many game objects checking for collisions. The physics engine
        uses basic billiard physics and elliptical physics. Additional physics components included in each sprite may include vectors for buoyancy,
        gravity, drag and force. The particle emitters are very diverse, they allow you to choose the number of particles, initial velocity, gravity,
        drag, duration, fade time, and max distance. If desired, a special derivation of the particle emitter allows for animations and their duration
        and speed.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="span-11 last" >
      <p>
        On top of all of the visual effects, the Dark Tide Team spent a tremendous amount of time on the sound effects and music. Keaton Robinson, a programmer
        with a background in music wrote the introduction and gameplay music. All of the soundeffects were foleyed or created with our voices with the help
        of a few extra voice actors. This excludes water splashes since microphones were destroyed trying to create those sound effects. The game contains a 
        sound manager due to the extensive amount of soundeffects capable of playing at one time. This makes sure sounds fade out, don't play if other sounds
        are already playing and get cut out if a higher priority sound is to be played. In total, the Dark Tide team created over 200 some sound effects for 
        this 3 minute game.
      </p>
      <h2>Game Rules</h2>
      <p>
        1. Two teams, red versus yellow. Preferred team size 1-2.<br />
        2. Urchins must attach to ships and sink them to obtain gold.<br />
        3. No penalty for messing with opponents urchins.<br />
        4. Knock enemy urchins off boats to take the boat over.<br /> 
        5. The team with the most gold at the end is the victor.<br />
      </p>
